---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Methodology | pedestrianaccidentcalc.com';
const description = 'How the pedestrian accident settlement calculator works: pain multipliers, comparative fault reduction, and state fault rules.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Methodology</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Aspen Lockwood (AL), Editor-in-Chief. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Pain and suffering multiplier</h2><p>Catastrophic: 7× medical costs + 2× lost wages. Severe: 5×/2×. Moderate: 3.5×/2×. Minor: 2×/2×. Higher multipliers for pedestrian accidents vs. standard car accidents reflect severity data — pedestrians have no crash protection and suffer disproportionately severe injuries.</p>
  <h2>Comparative fault reduction</h2><p>Gross damages reduced by the pedestrian&rsquo;s percentage of fault. Pure comparative fault: always reduces (never bars). Modified comparative fault: bars at ≥50% fault. Contributory negligence: any fault bars recovery entirely (Alabama, DC, Maryland, North Carolina, Virginia).</p>
  <h2>Range</h2><p>&plusmn;35–40% around the midpoint. Insurance policy limits, jury composition, and local verdict patterns introduce significant variability.</p>
</BaseLayout>
